The push to have hostages tell their stories has met with mixed reaction, former NSW state coroner John Abernethy suggesting a legal intervention could stop the interviews being aired. 

Former Victoria Premier Jeff Kennett was even more strident, suggesitng Sydney cafe siege hostages selling their stories to the media is 'just plain grubby'.

'Two innocent hostages lost their lives. I do not think it is morally right that the media pay, and any of those who were saved should profit from the attack. Just plain grubby,' Mr Kennett tweeted.

Cafe manager Tori Johnson and mother-of-three Katrina Dawson were killed when the 17-hour siege ended in a shoot-out in the early hours of December 16. 

